                     <interp inst="def1-1042-18490409" type="surname" value="LEONARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1042-18490409" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM LEONARD</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-1042-18490409" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1042-18490409" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1042-18490409" type="age" value="37"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1042-18490409" type="surname" value="RYAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1042-18490409" type="given" value="LAWRENCE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">LAWRENCE RYAN</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18490409-1042-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18490409-1042-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18490409-1042-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>, stealing 1 rope fender and 6lbs. weight of rope, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18490409-name-1190" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1190" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1190" type="surname" value="THRIFT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1190" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18490409-1042-offence-1 t18490409-name-1190"></join>James Thift</persName>, in a vessel in the <placeName id="t18490409-geo-7">
                        <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18490409-1042-offence-1 t18490409-geo-7"></join>Thames</placeName>. </rs>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SIMONDS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1191" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1191" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1191" type="surname" value="FINLATSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1191" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE FINLATSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the mate of the <hi rend="italic">Guildford</hi>, which was lying in the Mill-hole, Rotherhithe. On 30th March, we had a rope fender safe over the ship's side—I missed it when the police-inspector came—Mr. James Thift is captain and part owner of the ship—I have since seen the fender at the police-court—it is Mr. Thift's property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARNELL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is the master's name on the stern of the vessel? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; it is on the boats—the crew consists of six men forward, and me and the captain—I do not know whether the men had been backwards and forwards to the shore.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1192" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1192" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1192" type="surname" value="BRIDGES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1192" type="given" value="WILLIAM THOMAS"></interp>WILLIAM THOMAS BRIDGES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Thamet-police-inspector</hi>). I was on duty on 30th March, between twelve and one o'clock at night, and saw a boat fast to a barge between the <hi rend="italic">Guildford</hi> and <hi rend="italic">Enterprize</hi>—I went alongside with two constables—Elwick and Howe jumped out of our boat into the barge—Howe brought the prisoner Ryan to me, and found the fender in the barge—I said to Ryan, "How about this rope in the boat?"—he said a man sent him to the barge to get them—I said "What man?"—he said he did not know—Elwick then brought Leonard to me, and I asked him if the boat belonged to him—he said, "Yes"—I said, "What about this rope?"—he said a man had sent him who he did not know to get it, a traveller along-shore—this fender (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) is one lost from the <hi rend="italic">Guildford</hi>—I did not see it fonnd.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Where did you first see either of them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were brought to me by the constables in the barge where the fender was found.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18490409-name-1193" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1193" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1193" type="surname" value="ELLWICK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-name-1193" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ELLWICK</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Thames policeman</hi>, 27). I was on duty—I remember Bridges coming on board the barge—I brought the prisoner Leonard to him—I found this rope in the head of the barge—I saw Leonard with his hand upon another rope which hung down from the side of the <hi rend="italic">Guildford</hi>—I after<lb></lb>wards examined that, and found the piece I found Leonard with had been undone from that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> You found the rope belonging to the <hi rend="italic">Guildford</hi> in the barge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; the prisoner's boat was fastened to the barge—I heard them say a traveller told them to get it—the prisoners work for the Trinity Corporation, and this boat belonged to the Corporation—they had been</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184904090195"></xptr>
               <p>drinking, but were not drunk—they were sober enough to have charge of a boat.(The prisoners both received good characters.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">LEONARD</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18490409-1042-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-1042-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-1042-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 38.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">RYAN</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18490409-1042-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18490409-1042-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18490409-1042-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 37.</p>
